Choices:  Yeah No  A: Great  B: Not bad  <n><n><n>---<n><n>### Ai-Based Decision-Making<n><n>When a machine learning algorithm is trained on some data, the model can then provide an answer to test cases that it hasn't seen before based on what it knows. The machine is making predictions based on the data it has seen so far, and we can trust the model to be correct to the point that the model can still provide correct answers outside of its training data. That said:<n><n>* Machine Learning: Models that are trained on historical data (also called "supervised learning") are models that perform predictions that are grounded in a well-defined domain.<n><n>* Deep Learning: These are models that try to perform predictions that are more on a par with our brain's understanding of the world. <n><n><n>### Machine Learning<n><n>* Machine Learning can be an extremely fast and powerful way to develop models on top of large scale data.<n><n>* Deep learning works well with data from structured data sets that are fairly linear in their nature.<n><n>* Deep Neural Networks can be trained to extract non-linear, useful information from data.<n><n><n><n>### 1. Simple Text Classification<n><n>* Named Entity Recognition<n><n>* Text classification is the task of labeling a piece of text with a predefined label (think of this as putting the text in a category).<n><n>* Simple text classification is one of the most important problems in Natural Language Processing (NLP).<n><n>* For example, Named Entity Recognizers identify whether a given text mentions an entity such as a person, location or organization.<n><n>* In this exercise you're going to create a text classifier that classifies articles into one of two categories: News or Non-News.<n>What features/properties does it have?<n><n>* In this case the property is the word News, which can be found in many different positions in text, so to say, it is not that predictive. This is why we should include various other properties, such as the location of the word, the frequency, the size of it... and so on.<n><n>* Some examples: we can say that the News is located at the beginning, is 5 letters long, is before a capital letter<n>

Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input: They burned the record, they were trying to do what to history? Choices:  A: compact disc B: tape C: rewrite D: play music E: erase<n>Output: E: erase<n><n>Input: She sure didn't have a green thumb, every time she thought she was making grow something it would what? Choices:  A: growth B: flowering C: ground D: die E: plants<n>Output: D: die<n><n>Input:Bob's feet hurt from running barefoot on the hot pavement.  I lost his shoes, didn't know where they landed, and had to run from the corner store to his home.  About where did he run? Choices:  A: a bed of nails B: town C: attractive consistent look D: city block E: ground<n>Output:		A: a bed of sharp nails<n><n>###### Explanation:<n><n>Fabric is only cut to order if it comes from a curtain or tailor shop; cutting them in-store may be considered a service. The train station can only give answers for B, D and E - this was the only location that could'store' information related to the question. For every other question, the person who would use the thing must apply it or receive it; it cannot come out of thin air.<n><n>In general, I can't discern which of the things I need that have a direct relationship to my input are included in the set returned by get(item). This behavior is strange, and not in accordance with the way other things such as "cube of the first 20 Fibonacci numbers" work.<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input: They burned the record, they were trying to do what to history? Choices:  A: compact disc B: tape C: rewrite D: play music E: erase<n>Output: E: erase<n><n>Input: She sure didn't have a green thumb, every time she thought she was making grow something it would what? Choices:  A: growth B: flowering C: ground D: die E: plants<n>Output: D: die<n><n>Input:If you are driving too fast on an icy road you are being what? Choices:  A: deadly B: dangerous C: unconcerned D: stressful E: harder when weather bad<n>Output:		D: stressful<n>```python<n>class Solution(object):<n>    def singleWordSeeker(self,words,targetWord):<n>        # write your code here<n>        allwords = list(filter(lambda x:x!= '')<n>        match =  " ".join(reduce(lambda *x: x[0]+x[1]\<n>                if x[0] <= x[2] or x[3] <=x[2]\<n>                else x.pop(0))]<n>        if words == match:<n>            print(targetWord, " is the answer")<n>        else:<n>            print("The word doesn't exist")<n><n>        self.singleWordSeeker2 =self.singleWordSeekere<n>    def singleWord(self,words, targetWord):<n>        if self.checklist2 == targetWord:<n>            print(words[0] + "\n" + words)<n>```<n>```python<n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    x = Solution()<n>    arr = ["A tailor shop",<n>            "I wait for the train",<n>            "A oil station",<n>            "Sometimes marriage doesnt work",<n>            "A dresser",<n>            "She burned her CD's",<n>            "She killed our plants",<n>            "It was a dangerous drive",<n>            "It smells sweet",<n>            "I need this record",<n>            "Bed bugs",<n>            "An eraser",<n>            "She wasn't green",<n>            "My head hurts",<n>            "It's too hard"]<n>    for i in range(len(arr)):<n>        print(arr[i], end = " ")<n>    words,target = " ", " "<n>    while(len(words)!=len(target)):<n>        words = input()<n>        if len(arr) > 0:<n>            words+=[arr[0]]<n>            target = [x for x in arr[1:]]

Choices:  ABCDE<n>\end{code}<n><n>Answer: This approach is good, but be careful in using a `Dict` to replace all words with a string<n><n>\begin{code}<n>import sys<n><n>def process(query):<n>   words = query.split()<n>   return set((list(dictionary))[i] for i, i in enumerate(words))<n><n>words = dict.fromkeys(['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E'])<n><n>def handle(x):<n>    return''.join(words[i] for i in x.split())<n><n>with open("instructions.txt", 'r') as f:<n>    # read the file line by line<n>    for line in f:<n>        print(line)<n>        print(f"Input: {process(line)}")<n>        print(f'Output: "{handle(process(line))}"')<n>\end{code]<n><n>Instead, what you should do is create a dictionary that has the `List` type entry as key instead of `string`, something like this :<n><n>\begin{blockquote}<n>\strong{Dictionary type : \strong{Dict}<n>\end{blockquote}<n><n>\begin{itemize}<n>\item \strong{Parameters :}<n>\item key : `str`<n>\item value : `List[List[Type]]`<n>\item Iterative : \strong{No}<n>\item Built-in : \strong{yes}<n>\item Method : \strong{No.}<n>\end{itemize}<n><n>\begininput1}<n>\end{itemize}\\<n><n>Comment: Hey @GhostRider! So, what you're saying is that, you could use a `Dict` to represent each `choice` but then, you couldn't use a `Dict` which represents the `letter` of the `choice` to represent the respective `choice`?<n><n>Comment: I got it now :)

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input: They burned the record, they were trying to do what to history? Choices:  A: compact disc B: tape C: rewrite D: play music E: erase<n>Output: E: erase<n><n>Input: She sure didn't have a green thumb, every time she thought she was making grow something it would what? Choices:  A: growth B: flowering C: ground D: die E: plants<n>Output: D: die<n><n>Input:Where may I view sharks in a clear tunnel? Choices:  A: south pacific B: sea world C: pacific ocean D: indian ocean E: gulf of mexico<n>Output:		C: pacific ocean<n><n>Input: He is a really busy person, he makes lots of plans to keep him busy. What type of schedule might he use? Choices:  Choices: A: daily B: weekly C: monthly D: yearly E: decade<n>Output: E: decade<n>Input: This person is very uncomfortable at family functions. She is very good at expressing her dislike for people. What does she like? Choices: <n>Choices: A: intimate conversations B: having fun C: being outside <n>D: friends and family members E: silence<n>Output: E: silence<n><n>Input: The teacher told her to wait for her friends, but she doesn't like being left alone. What is probably going to take place? Choices: Choices: A: she will hang out with all friends even if it takes longer B: she will start to play quietly so she takes a break from her friends C: she will leave the house early and catch her friends D: she will go to another friend to catch her friends E: she will stay outside to talk to other people<n>Output: D: she will go from friend to friend to catch her friends<n><n>#!/usr/bin/python<n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*-<n>from __future__ import print_function<n>from functools import reduce<n>import re<n>import sys<n><n><n>l1, l2,l3 = []<n>def readall ():<n>    line = sys.stdin.readline()<n>    # print(line)<n>    if not line:<n>        return<n>    # print(len(line))<n>    tokens = line.split(" ")<n>    tokensl1 = []<n>    for toke in tokens:<n>        # print(toke[0:4])<n>        if toke[0:4] == 'type of':<n>            tokensl1.append(toke)<n>    for toke2 in tokensl1:<n>        l1.append(tokensl1.index(toke2))<n>        l1.extend(range(l1[tokensl1.indexOf(toke2)+1],l2))<n>        l2.append(tokens[tokensl1[tokens.index(toke[::4])]+1])<n><n><n>

Then generate words starting with the 1st letter of 5 letter word and ending with the last letter of the word.<n>"""<n>def readInput(x):<n>    infile = open(x, 'r')<n>    print (infile.read().split('\n'))<n>    infile.close<n>    <n>def do(n):<n>    while n>0:<n>        i=n-1<n>        y=str(i)<n>        while y>=0:<n>            try:<n>                p=str(input())[::-1]<n>            except UnboundLocalError:<n>                #if we are not given a word of 5 letters we can not produce any word<n>                raise IndexError<n>            if len(p)==5:<n>                j=len(p)<n>                s=''<n>                <n>                while j>=1:<n>                    s=s+str(p[0])<n>                    i=i-6<n>                    y=str(i)[::-1]<n>                    j=j-1<n>                if len(s)>0:<n>                    p[0]=s<n>                    <n>            n=n-1#remove one, so we go in again<n>        if n==0:<n>            end=i<n>        y=''<n>        n=end+1<n>        <n>##################################################################                               <n>input='4Task1

Choices: 1: in the middle 2: on the corners 3: on the sides 4: on the top 5: in the bottom 6: on the right side 7: in a darkroom 8: on the left side 9: to the sides 10: at home<n>Output: 2: on the right and left sides<n><n>Input:What does an apple tree look like? Choices:	1: an apple 2: a lemon 3: a banana 4: lemon tree 5: an orange tree 6: a mango tree 7: banana tree 8: pine tree 9: peach tree 10: a cherry tree 11: apple tree 12: a grapefruit tree 13: a walnut tree 14: nectarine tree 15: grapefruit tree<n>Output: 11:apple tree<n><n>Input:What do you eat a watermelon? Choices:1: in a fork2: with a knife3: with a glass4: as a whole5: with an ice cream scoop6: with your hands7: with a spoon8: with a spork9: a fork and spoon10: with a knife<n>Output: 7: with a spork<n><n>#!/usr/bin/python<n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*-<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def judge(self, wordDict):<n>        judge = ""<n>        for word, definition in wordDict.items():<n>            if definition:<n>                judge = judge + "%s means %s" % (word, definition)<n>        return judge<n><n># Driver code<n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    s = Solution()<n>    #word = input("Enter word: ")<n>    word = "sail"<n>    definition = input("Enter definition(no definition=s): ")<n>    print(s.judge({"sail": "a sail"})== word + definition)<n>    #print(s.judge() == word + definition)<n>

(D) D.<n>Output: A: It crashed and needed restored.<n><n>How did that person know they would win the lottery<n><n><pre><n>1 A: probably<n>2 B: certainly</pre><n><n><div class='answer'><n>answer = ['A','B']<n>if(answer.random(2))<n>       print('A: probably')<n>elseif(answer.random()<.4 )<n>        print('B: certainly')<n>else<n>         print('Wrong')<n>     </div><n><n>

Choices:  What: C:  A: wet ground B: swimming in the ocean C: raining D: running in a puddle E: swamped<n>Output: None of the above<n><n>### Part Two:<n><n>I. Do some research on Amazon Mechanical Turk, learn about the service and understand how to register an account and perform human tasks that could be performed by Alexa skills.<n><n>II. Find a few Mechanical Turk Requesters or those that hire Mechanical Turk workers to perform tasks. If you aren't comfortable with reading public forums you can search for information on Alexa Skills in the Amazon marketplace.<n><n>III. Select a couple of those tasks, perform them and report your findings.<n><n>IV. Search for information on how to code for Alexa Skills, if you are not comfortable with coding, do some research on how to design an Alexa skill without coding.<n><n>### Part Three:<n><n>I. Pick a real word and create a simple sentence that can be read as data about that word.<n><n>II. Write a small script that accepts text as input. From that text, if you're able to detect and make sense of the word, then do some simple data retrieval from a given open source lexicon. An example: you enter the word 'car', your script reads 'car' as valid input and searches the lexicon using 'car' as a search term and returns a count of all 'car' words. If you're able to find a lexicon this is very simple to get started with, show how you could build more complex lexicons.<n><n>### Additional Resources:<n><n>Instructions:<n>https://medium.com/@joshuagarfield/using-alexa-to-get-things-done-5935c81722c1#.x7y38i5a5<n>

Because people are hungry, the health of our society suffers. Hunger has adverse impact on a country's economy, because if people are healthy, they can contribute a productive society for many years to come. When people are not healthy, they have shorter workdays, and are less productive and prone to illness, further decreasing their and the society's productivity. There also are adverse health consequences in the short- and long-term. Short-term impacts result when children and adult

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Fabric is cut to order at what type of seller? Choices:  A: curtains B: tailor shop C: clothing store D: sewing room E: hardware store<n>Output: B: tailor shop<n><n>Input: Where are you if your reading magazines while waiting for a vehicle on rails? Choices:  A: vegetables B: market C: doctor D: train station E: bookstore<n>Output: D: train station<n><n>Input: What would need oil to be used? Choices:  A: ground B: human  body C: repair shop D: combustion engines E: service station<n>Output: D: combustion engines<n><n>Input: What is person probably feeling that plans on stopping being married to their spouse? Choices:  A: detachment B: bankruptcy C: sad D: fights E: wrong<n>Output: A: detachment<n><n>Input: What could you use to store a clock? Choices:  A: shelf B: own bedroom C: desk D: wall E: car<n>Output: A: shelf<n><n>Input: The person put on lotion, what did they want? Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input: They burned the record, they were trying to do what to history? Choices:  A: compact disc B: tape C: rewrite D: play music E: erase<n>Output: E: erase<n><n>Input: She sure didn't have a green thumb, every time she thought she was making grow something it would what? Choices:  A: growth B: flowering C: ground D: die E: plants<n>Output: D: die<n><n>Input:The president had to make a decision regarding the hate attack on his country, what did he do? Choices:  A: wage war B: fight enemy C: kill D: destroy enemy E: attacked his country<n>Output:		A: wage war<n><n>### Explanation<n><n># Solution Code<n>```python<n>def sol(inst):<n>  if inst.split()[0][-1] =='s' or inst.split()[1][-1] == s:<n>    answer = ((inst.split()[0].split(' at')[0]) + (inst.split()[1].split(' at')[1]))<n>  if inst.startswith(('Who ')) and inst.endswith(' what they do? '):<n>    answer = (inst.split('what they do')[1].strip()).split(' or ')[1]<n>  return answer<n><n>print sol(['What does Babe Ruth do?', 'Reads books at night.'])]<n>```<n>

Choices:  A: fresh smell B: good credit C: smooth skin D: fresh produce E: headache<n>Output: C: smooth skin<n><n>Input: They burned the record, they were trying to do what to history? Choices:  A: cold B: unfamiliar C: unknown D: unacquainted E: shy<n>Output:		E: shy<n>input: Why the pantyhose don't fit, they were trying out what to their body? Choices:  N/A<n><n>### Input:<n>```c<n>a<n>```<n><n>### Output:<n><n>```json<n>[ 1, 1, 2, 4, 4, 1, 4, 2, 3, 1, 1]<n>```<n><n>## Solution<n><n>```js<n>let arr = [1, 2, 'a', 1, 1];<n><n>function filter(input){<n>    let result = [];<n>    for (let i = 0; i < input.length; i++) {<n>        let obj = input[i];<n>        if (obj === arr[i]) {<n>            result.push(obj);<n>        } else {<n>            input[i] = undefined;<n>        }<n>    }<n>    return result;<n>}<n><n>function solution(){<n>    return filter(input);<n>}<n>```<n>## Result<n><n>```js<n>console.log(solution()[0])<n>// -> 7<n>console.log(typeof solution()[0])<n>/* -> (7) */<n>console.log(Object.values(solution())[0])<n>// [7]<n>```<n>

Choices: 	A: coffee B: nuts C: hot dogs D: pasta E: popcorn<n>Output: D: pasta<n><n>#---------------------------------------------------------------------------Implement the function findAnswer above<n>#----------------------------------------------------#Fucntion Head<n>def findAnswer(question):<n>    answer=question.lower()<n>    answerDict={}<n>    with open('dict_answers.txt') as dictfile:<n>        for line in dictfile:<n>            #print(line)<n>            data=line.split(":")<n>            answerDict[data[0].lower()]=data[1].replace("\n"," ").replace("\r"," ")<n><n>    for k,v in answerDict.items():<n>        answer=re.compile(v).findall(answer)<n>        if len(answer)>=1:<n>            return answer[0]<n>    return ''<n><n>#--------------------------------Implement the function answerInput above<n>#------------------------------------------#function Head<n>def answerInput(question):<n>    return findAnswer(question)<n><n>#-----------------------------------------------Implement the function guess and write the code<n>#----------------------------------------------#Fucntion head<n>def guess(input_string):<n>    answer={}<n>    with open('answers_correct_or_incorrect.txt') as correct_incorrect:<n>        for line_str in correct_incorrect: line = line_str.split(":") answer[(line_str.split("=")[0]):]=(line_str.split('=')[1].replace(" \n \r"," ").replace("'","\"").replace('.","\"."))<n><n>    for element in answer:<n>        if answer[element] == input_string:<n>            return True<n>    return False<n><n>#-----------------------------------------Implement the function outputString<n>#------------------------------------------ #Fucntion Head <n><n>def outputString(answer):<n>    with open('output.txt','r') as read:<n>        output='\n'+read.read()+'\n'+answer.replace("'","\"")[:-1]+' \n '<n>    return output<n><n>#------------------------------------

List two examples of each type.<n><n>Answer: <n><n>Direct-<n><n>You want to know if the house owner owns his own property he is living in, and wants to own it.<n><n>"Does the owner of the house own the house, does the house belong to the owner of the house, or is the mortgagee the rightful owner?<n><n>"Does the house and lot belong to Jose, or not?"<n><n>"Does the lady own the shoes or does someone else?"<n><n>Indirect -<n><n>You are a seller in a hardware store. A young boy comes in and asks you,<n><n>"Is there any toilet paper left?"<n><n>You ask,<n><n>"Did you find any toilet paper in the other section?"<n><n>You would assume that he is seeking to know if there is or isn't any toilet paper for sale, and that he does not know.<n><n>Rhetorical-<n><n>This is a type of question that someone makes when that do not expect to get an answer. This is often used to make a point.<n><n>Ex.<n><n>"Did you not know the rules of the road?"<n><n>"Did you have to break the rule to get through?"<n><n>When you ask an rhetorical question, you are trying to make a point. You are not looking for an answer to the question. You believe that the listener will already know the answer, but you ask as a way to make a point. So yes or no answers to a rhetorical question are not needed. It is a question asked for effect rather than information.<n><n><n><n><n>What are the four steps of the logical argument?<n><n>Answer: 1.Premise<n><n>Premise can be a statement, question, idea, etc.<n><n>The following statement:<n><n>2.Major Premise<n><n>-Sometimes the premise is a question, and you can only find it out on your own or with your friends.<n><n>The following question:

Custom implies someone who does the cutting to spec. Curtain stores do this.<n><n>## The second question is B: train stations<n><n>Since a person looking for magazines is going to be bored and waiting for something the next closest thing would be reading material. Reading material = Books. Books = Magazines. Choices:  1. Shop A: using soap to clean 2. Shop B: using a brush 3. Shop C: using hot water  4. Shop D: drying it 5. Shop E: conditioning.<n>Output: 3. Shop B: Using a brush<n><n>```<n>Explanation: You would shampoo your hair by simply brushing it, which is the most common way<n>```<n><n>## Solution<n>```<n>################################################################################<n># Author : Cui Yu<n># Created Time: 2020-06-19 15:24<n>###############################################################################<n>####################################################################<n>#  : In this sample program, we discuss some questions about common<n>##################################<n># <n># > ifelsewhilefordobreakcontinue.<n># > <n>#################################################################<n>class Solution(object):<n>  def solution(self, answers, ans1, ans2):<n>    """<n>    :type answers: List[str]<n>    :type ans1: str<n>    :type ans2: str<n>    :rtype: List[str] <n>    """<n>      ans = ""<n>      if ans1 == ans2: ans += "There is only one answer."<n>      else:<n>        ans += ans1 + " and " + ans2 + " are both answers."<n><n>      for i in answers:<n>        if i in ans:<n>            i == "True"<n>            Ans += i + ", "<n>            ans += i + ","<n>
